*[TPI Composites] Defect Detection in Wind Turbine Blade Manufacturing*
_2/15/2024_

*Purpose*
• The meeting aimed to address the primary issue of defect detection in wind turbine blades and its financial implications.

*Focus Areas*
• Defect types and detection methods
• Manufacturing workflow and quality assurance processes
• Environmental conditions affecting defect detection
• Stakeholder roles and responsibilities

*Key Takeaways*
• Defects primarily involve dry spots and wrinkles, with significant financial implications estimated at $30-50 million.
• Current defect detection is manual and challenging, especially after blades are fully assembled.
• Environmental factors such as lighting and dust are concerns that need to be managed.
• The QA team currently uses manual, paper-based processes without standardization.

*Risks / Open Questions*
• How effective are current lighting conditions for defect detection?
• What specific measures can be implemented to improve the QA process?
• What are the potential impacts of environmental conditions on defect detection?

*Recommended Next Steps*
• Explore the feasibility of improving lighting and camera placement for better defect detection.
• Consider developing a standardized method for capturing and organizing defect data.
• Investigate the need for protective camera cases to withstand manufacturing conditions.
